2500|$|The <b>iron</b> <b>sight</b> {{line was}} {{redesigned}} and featured a rear receiver aperture battle sight calibrated for [...] {{with an additional}} ladder aperture sight that could be flipped up and was calibrated for [...] in [...] increments. This sight line like other aperture sight lines proved to be faster and more accurate than the typical mid-barrel rear sight elements sight lines offered by Mauser, previous Lee–Enfields or the Buffington battle sight of the 1903 Springfield.|$|E
2500|$|The No. 5 <b>iron</b> <b>sight</b> {{line was}} similar to the No. 4 marks and {{featured}} a rear receiver aperture battle sight calibrated for [...] with an additional ladder aperture sight that could be flipped up and was calibrated for [...] in [...] increments. The No. 5 Mk I was popular with soldiers owing to its light weight, portability and shorter length than a standard Lee–Enfield rifle. The No. 5 was first issued to the British 1st Airborne Division and used during their liberation of Denmark and Norway in 1945. BSA-Shirley, Birmingham produced 81329 rifles and ROF Fazakerley, Liverpool 169807 rifles.|$|E
